# 3. Provider Lifecycle Rules

## autoDispose

- [ ] default to `autoDispose`
- [ ] prevents memory leaks and stale state
- [ ] ensures clean feature lifecycle

---

## keepAlive

Only use `keepAlive` when:

- auth session state
- global app configuration
- cached critical data

---

## Rule

> If state is feature-scoped â†’ autoDispose  
> If state is app-global â†’ keepAlive (explicitly justified)

---

# 4. Riverpod Access Rules

## read vs watch vs listen

| Method | Purpose |
|--------|--------|
| `ref.watch()` | reactive UI rebuilds |
| `ref.read()` | one-time access (callbacks only) |
| `ref.listen()` | side-effects (navigation, snackbars, logging) |

---

## MUST

- [ ] use `ref.watch()` inside `build()`
- [ ] use `ref.read()` ONLY in callbacks / event handlers
- [ ] use `ref.listen()` for side-effects

---

## MUST NOT

- âťŚ use `ref.read()` inside `build()` for values that should trigger rebuilds (reading `.notifier` in event handlers / `initState` is OK)
- âťŚ trigger side-effects in `build()`
- âťŚ mix read/watch incorrectly causing stale UI

---

# 5. AsyncValue Handling (CRITICAL)

All async providers MUST handle:

- loading
- data
- error

---

## Required Pattern

- [ ] use `.when()` in UI
- [ ] never assume `.value` exists
- [ ] display user-friendly error states

---

## Anti-Pattern

- âťŚ `.value!` without null handling
- âťŚ ignoring loading/error states
- âťŚ leaking exceptions to UI

---

# 6. Performance Rules

## MUST

- [ ] use `select()` for granular rebuilds
- [ ] avoid watching entire provider when only a field is needed
- [ ] split providers for large state objects

---

## Example Principle

> Prefer: watching a field  
> Over: watching entire state object

---

# 7. Provider Design Rules

## Provider Families

- [ ] use `.family` for parameterized providers
- [ ] avoid global parameter storage inside providers

---

## Separation of Concerns

- data providers â†’ fetch/store data
- domain providers â†’ business logic
- presentation providers â†’ UI state only

---

# 8. Side-Effects Rules

## MUST

- [ ] use `ref.listen()` for:
  - navigation
  - snackbars
  - analytics
  - logging

---

## MUST NOT

- âťŚ perform side-effects in provider `build()`
- âťŚ trigger UI actions from `ref.watch()`
- âťŚ mix state updates with navigation logic

---

# 9. Testing Requirements

- [ ] use `ProviderContainer` for unit tests
- [ ] override dependencies explicitly
- [ ] test state transitions (initial â†’ loading â†’ data/error)
- [ ] test notifier methods independently

---

# 10. Forbidden Patterns

## MUST NOT

- âťŚ use BLoC / Cubit patterns
- âťŚ use Provider package (only `flutter_riverpod`)
- âťŚ use global mutable state
- âťŚ embed business logic in widgets
- âťŚ use `setState` for anything other than ephemeral UI

---

# 11. Anti-Patterns (COMMON FAILURES)

- overusing `StateProvider` for complex state
- duplicating state across multiple providers
- using `ref.read()` incorrectly in UI
- ignoring AsyncValue states
- leaking async errors directly to UI

